<TITLE> Govt to ask for extradition of Mujib's killers </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 11 (bdnews24.com)Home minister Sahara Khatun has said Bangladesh will seek assistance from the member countries of Interpol to extradite the fugitive convicts of 'Bangabandhu' Sheikh Mujibur Rahman murder. "The convicts have been absconding in many countries. I will ask the countries to extradite them," Khatun said at Zia International Airport early on Sunday before leaving for Singapore to join the 78th assembly session of Interpol conference, according to private TV Channel-i. Independence hero and president Sheikh Mujib was assassinated along with most of his family members by renegade army officers on Aug 15, 1975. After the Awami League government came to power in 1996, a case was filed with Dhanmondi Police Station against 24 persons. On Nov 8, 1998, Dhaka sessions judge Golam Rasul awarded death sentences to 15 of the 20 accused. Four of the convicts major (retd) Bazlul Huda, Lt Col (dismissed) Syed Faruk Rahman, Lt Col (retd) Sultan Shahriar Rashid Khan and Lt Col (retd) Mohiuddin Ahmed appealed to the High Court against the verdict. On Dec 14, 2000 the High Court gave a split verdictJustice Mohammed Ruhul Amin upheld death sentences of 10 of the convicts but Justice A B M Khairul Haque retained death sentences of all 15. On Apr 30, 2001 Justice Mohammad Fazlul Karim of a third High Court bench upheld death sentences of 12 and acquitted three. Home ministers of 38 countries are attending the five-day long Interpol conference for the first time. Police chiefs of 187 countries are also joining the meet. The home minister is scheduled to return home on Oct 17. b
